{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778291043,"nonce":"JO/3qYSRn/xWx1LDqz9uX8v/Sds=","message":"## 2×2×2 Baseline Matrix: Variance Analysis Results\n\n**Experiment:** 2×2×2 matrix — architecture (GRU vs vRNN) × smoothness (nn_hidden_derivative 0.001 vs off) × jerk (nn_output_jerk 1e5 vs off). 5 replicates per cell, 12k warmup batches, batch size 250. Metric: pairwise RMSE on post-go (t ∈ [0, 1.0 s]) mean forward-velocity profile (direction-averaged across 8 validation targets). Within-cell: C(5,2)=10 pairs; NN across-cell: 5×5=25 pairs per pair of cells.\n\n### 8-Cell Variance Table\n\n| Cell label | Arch | Smooth | Jerk | Within RMSE | NN-Across RMSE | Ratio |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| GRU / none | GRU | off | off | 0.391 | 0.271 | 1.443 |\n| GRU / smooth | GRU | on | off | 0.264 | 0.203 | 1.296 |\n| **GRU / jerk** | **GRU** | **off** | **on** | **0.112** | **0.147** | **0.758** |\n| GRU / smooth+jerk | GRU | on | on | 0.194 | 0.147 | 1.315 |\n| vRNN / none | vRNN | off | off | 0.034 | 0.026 | 1.338 |\n| vRNN / smooth | vRNN | on | off | 0.030 | 0.029 | 1.021 |\n| vRNN / jerk | vRNN | off | on | 0.025 | 0.021 | 1.194 |\n| vRNN / smooth+jerk | vRNN | on | on | 0.023 | 0.021 | 1.105 |\n\n### Winner\n\n**GRU / jerk** is the only cell with ratio \u003c 1.0 (0.758). Within-cell RMSE 0.112 m/s — a 71% reduction vs the GRU/none baseline (0.391). This is the best result, but the ratio is not yet 'acceptable' per the original goal.\n\n### Key Findings\n\n1. **Jerk alone is the primary driver for GRU.** Adding jerk penalty dropped within-RMSE from 0.391 to 0.112 (71% reduction). Smoothness alone achieved only 33% reduction (0.391 → 0.264).\n2. **Combining smooth+jerk is worse than jerk alone.** GRU/smooth+jerk ratio = 1.315 vs GRU/jerk ratio = 0.758 — the two terms interfere with each other.\n3. **vRNN cells under-converged at 12k batches.** Final train losses: GRU ≈ 3.7, vRNN ≈ 10+. All vRNN cells produce nearly-identical velocity profiles (low absolute within-cell RMSE 0.02–0.03) but cluster tightly together — suggesting insufficient training rather than genuine variability reduction. NN-across RMSE is also very low (~0.02), so cross-cell variation is also small.\n4. **vRNN ratio never drops below 1.0.** Best vRNN ratio is 1.021 (vRNN/smooth). Low absolute RMSE but still ratio \u003e 1 throughout.\n\n### Replicate Clustering (User Observation)\n\nIn GRU/jerk and GRU/smooth+jerk: 3/5 replicates cluster tightly; 2/5 deviate (slower, less bell-shaped velocity profile). The 0.758 ratio reflects this mixture. Outlier-exclusion (dropping the 2 deviants) would improve the ratio but is not the preferred path — it would require a post-hoc justification for exclusion.\n\n### Status\n\nNot adopting GRU+jerk as default yet. 0.758 ratio is encouraging but the replicate clustering issue needs resolution first. Further escalation TBD.\n\n### Escalation Paths (Cross-Refs)\n\n- vRNN tau-sweep filed: TBD (see filing below)\n- Analytical Riccati hyperparameter sweep: TBD (see filing below)\n- Empirical cost-schedule sweep: `6ec6b19` (existing)\n- Outlier-exclusion as fallback: documented but not preferred at this stage\n\n### Artifacts\n\n- Variance findings doc: `/tmp/flavor_ab_review/findings/variance_matrix_results.md`\n- Velocity plots: `/tmp/flavor_ab_review/plots/` (HTML, not committed — too large)\n- Run-specs: `results/part2_5/runs/baseline_jerk_vrnn_matrix__*/run.json` (committed on `feature/baseline-matrix-results`)","files":null}]}